05253nam a22008055i 9780231550536DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018060444  a97802315505367 a10.7312/brow193842doi  a(DE-B1597)526840  a(OCoLC)1103219631  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC423b.B83 2019 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a306.209182/12231 aBrown, Wendy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Ruins of Neoliberalism :bThe Rise of Antidemocratic Politics in the West /cWendy Brown. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Wellek Library Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Society Must Be Dismantled -- t2. Politics Must Be Dethroned -- t3. The Personal, Protected Sphere Must Be Extended -- t4. Speaking Wedding Cakes and Praying Pregnancy Centers: Religious Liberty and Free Speech in Neoliberal Jurisprudence -- t5. No Future for White Men: Nihilism, Fatalism, and Ressentiment -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the West, hard-right leaders are surging to power on platforms of ethno-economic nationalism, Christianity, and traditional family values. Is this phenomenon the end of neoliberalism or its monstrous offspring?In the Ruins of Neoliberalism casts the hard-right turn as animated by socioeconomically aggrieved white working- and middle-class populations but contoured by neoliberalism’s multipronged assault on democratic values. From its inception, neoliberalism flirted with authoritarian liberalism as it warred against robust democracy. It repelled social-justice claims through appeals to market freedom and morality. It sought to de-democratize the state, economy, and society and re-secure the patriarchal family. In key works of the founding neoliberal intellectuals, Wendy Brown traces the ambition to replace democratic orders with ones disciplined by markets and traditional morality and democratic states with technocratic ones.Yet plutocracy, white supremacy, politicized mass affect, indifference to truth, and extreme social disinhibition were no part of the neoliberal vision. Brown theorizes their unintentional spurring by neoliberal reason, from its attack on the value of society and its fetish of individual freedom to its legitimation of inequality. Above all, she argues, neoliberalism’s intensification of nihilism coupled with its accidental wounding of white male supremacy generates an apocalyptic populism willing to destroy the world rather than endure a future in which this supremacy disappears.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aDemocracyxSocial aspectszWestern countries. 0aNeoliberalismxPolitical aspectszWestern countries. 0aPolitical culturezWestern countries. 0aPopulismzWestern countries. 0aRight and left (Political science)zWestern countries. 0aRight-wing extremistszWestern countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishz978311061055008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019z9783110606423oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/brow1938440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231550536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cov